# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: text-classification
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] The **bag-of-words** (**BoW**) **model** is a model of text which uses an unordered collection (a "bag") of words.
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] It is used in natural language processing and information retrieval (IR).
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] It disregards word order (and thus most of syntax or grammar) but captures multiplicity.
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] The bag-of-words model is commonly used in methods of document classification where, for example, the (frequency of) occurrence of each word is used as a feature for training a classifier.
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] It has also been used for computer vision.
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] An early reference to "bag of words" in a linguistic context can be found in Zellig Harris's 1954 article on *Distributional Structure*.
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] The following models a text document using bag-of-words.
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] Each key is the word, and each value is the number of occurrences of that word in the given text document.
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] It is also what we expect from a strict *JSON object* representation.
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] So, as we see in the bag algebra, the "union" of two documents in the bags-of-words representation is, formally, the disjoint union, summing the multiplicities of each element.
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] The BoW representation of a text removes all word ordering.
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] For example, the BoW representation of "man bites dog" and "dog bites man" are the same, so any algorithm that operates with a BoW representation of text must treat them in the same way.
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] Despite this lack of syntax or grammar, BoW representation is fast and may be sufficient for simple tasks that do not require word order.
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] and so the BoW representation would be insufficient to determine the detailed meaning of the document.
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] Implementations of the bag-of-words model might involve using frequencies of words in a document to represent its contents.
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] The frequencies can be "normalized" by the inverse of document frequency, or tf–idf.
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] Additionally, for the specific purpose of classification, supervised alternatives have been developed to account for the class label of a document.
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] Lastly, binary (presence/absence or 1/0) weighting is used in place of frequencies for some problems (e.g., this option is implemented in the WEKA machine learning software system).
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] A common alternative to using dictionaries is the hashing trick, where words are mapped directly to indices with a hash function.
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] When using a hash function, no memory is required to store a dictionary.
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] In practice, hashing simplifies the implementation of bag-of-words models and improves scalability.
[src:text-classification/bag-of-words-model] Collisions can occur when two words are hashed to the same index, but this happens infrequently and may function as a form of regularization.
[src:text-classification/document-classification] The documents to be classified may be texts, images, music, etc.
[src:text-classification/document-classification] Each kind of document possesses its special classification problems.
[src:text-classification/document-classification] When not otherwise specified, **text classification** is implied.
[src:text-classification/document-classification] Documents may be classified according to their subjects or according to other attributes (such as document type, author, printing year etc.).
[src:text-classification/document-classification] In the rest of this article only subject classification is considered.
[src:text-classification/document-classification] There are two main philosophies of subject classification of documents: the content-based approach and the request-based approach.
[src:text-classification/document-classification] Request-oriented classification may be classification that is targeted towards a particular audience or user group.
[src:text-classification/document-classification] For example, a library or a database for feminist studies may classify/index documents differently when compared to a historical library.
[src:text-classification/document-classification] It is probably better, however, to understand request-oriented classification as *policy-based classification*: The classification is done according to some ideals and reflects the purpose of the library or database doing the classification.
[src:text-classification/document-classification] In this way it is not necessarily a kind of classification or indexing based on user studies.
[src:text-classification/document-classification] Only if empirical data about use or users are applied should request-oriented classification be regarded as a user-based approach.
[src:text-classification/document-classification] Sometimes a distinction is made between assigning documents to classes ("classification") versus assigning subjects to documents ("subject indexing") but as Frederick Wilfrid Lancaster has argued, this distinction is not fruitful.
[src:text-classification/document-classification] "These terminological distinctions,” he writes, “are quite meaningless and only serve to cause confusion” (Lancaster, 2003, p.
[src:text-classification/document-classification] The view that this distinction is purely superficial is also supported by the fact that a classification system may be transformed into a thesaurus and vice versa (cf., Aitchison, 1986, 2004; Broughton, 2008; Riesthuis & Bliedung, 1991).
[src:text-classification/document-classification] Therefore, assigning a subject term to a document in an index is equivalent to assigning that document to the class of documents indexed by that term (all documents indexed or classified as X belong to the same class of documents).
[src:text-classification/document-classification] There are several software products under various license models available.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] In statistics, **naive** (sometimes **simple** or **idiot's**) **Bayes classifiers** are a family of "probabilistic classifiers" which assume that the features are conditionally independent, given the target class.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] In other words, a naive Bayes model assumes the information about the class provided by each variable is unrelated to the information from the others, with no information shared between the predictors.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] The highly unrealistic nature of this assumption, called the **naive independence assumption**, is what gives the classifier its name.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] These classifiers are some of the simplest Bayesian network models.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Naive Bayes classifiers generally perform worse than more advanced models like logistic regressions, especially at quantifying uncertainty (with naive Bayes models often producing wildly overconfident probabilities).
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] However, they are highly scalable, requiring only one parameter for each feature or predictor in a learning problem.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Maximum-likelihood training can be done by evaluating a closed-form expression (simply by counting observations in each group), rather than the expensive iterative approximation algorithms required by most other models.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Despite the use of Bayes' theorem in the classifier's decision rule, naive Bayes is not (necessarily) a Bayesian method, and naive Bayes models can be fit to data using either Bayesian or frequentist methods.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Naive Bayes is a simple technique for constructing classifiers: models that assign class labels to problem instances, represented as vectors of feature values, where the class labels are drawn from some finite set.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] There is not a single algorithm for training such classifiers, but a family of algorithms based on a common principle: all naive Bayes classifiers assume that the value of a particular feature is independent of the value of any other feature, given the class variable.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] For example, a fruit may be considered to be an apple if it is red, round, and about 10 cm in diameter.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] A naive Bayes classifier considers each of these features to contribute independently to the probability that this fruit is an apple, regardless of any possible correlations between the color, roundness, and diameter features.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] In many practical applications, parameter estimation for naive Bayes models uses the method of maximum likelihood; in other words, one can work with the naive Bayes model without accepting Bayesian probability or using any Bayesian methods.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Despite their naive design and apparently oversimplified assumptions, naive Bayes classifiers have worked quite well in many complex real-world situations.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] In 2004, an analysis of the Bayesian classification problem showed that there are sound theoretical reasons for the apparently implausible efficacy of naive Bayes classifiers.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Still, a comprehensive comparison with other classification algorithms in 2006 showed that Bayes classification is outperformed by other approaches, such as boosted trees or random forests.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] An advantage of naive Bayes is that it only requires a small amount of training data to estimate the parameters necessary for classification.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] The problem with the above formulation is that if the number of features n is large or if a feature can take on a large number of values, then basing such a model on probability tables is infeasible.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] The model must therefore be reformulated to make it more tractable.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] In practice, there is interest only in the numerator of that fraction, because the denominator does not depend on C and the values of the features $x_{i}$ are given, so that the denominator is effectively constant.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Now the "naive" conditional independence assumptions come into play: assume that all features in $\mathbf {x}$ are mutually independent, conditional on the category $C_{k}$ .
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Often, it is only necessary to discriminate between classes.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] One is that it allows an interpretation in information theory, where log-probabilities are units of information in nats.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Another is that it avoids arithmetic underflow.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] The discussion so far has derived the independent feature model, that is, the naive Bayes probability model.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] The naive Bayes classifier combines this model with a decision rule.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] One common rule is to pick the hypothesis that is most probable so as to minimize the probability of misclassification; this is known as the *maximum *a posteriori** or *MAP* decision rule.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] The assumptions on distributions of features are called the "event model" of the naive Bayes classifier.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] For discrete features like the ones encountered in document classification (include spam filtering), multinomial and Bernoulli distributions are popular.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] These assumptions lead to two distinct models, which are often confused.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] When dealing with continuous data, a typical assumption is that the continuous values associated with each class are distributed according to a normal (or Gaussian) distribution.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] For example, suppose the training data contains a continuous attribute, **x**.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] The data is first segmented by the class, and then the mean and variance of x is computed in each class.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Let $\mu _{k}$ be the mean of the values in x associated with class $C_{k}$ , and let $\sigma _{k}^{2}$ be the Bessel corrected variance of the values in x associated with class $C_{k}$ .
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Suppose one has collected some observation value v .
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Then, the probability *density* of v given a class $C_{k}$ , i.e., $p(x=v\mid C_{k})$ , can be computed by plugging v into the equation for a normal distribution parameterized by $\mu _{k}$ and $\sigma _{k}^{2}$ .
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Another common technique for handling continuous values is to use binning to discretize the feature values and obtain a new set of Bernoulli-distributed features.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Some literature suggests that this is required in order to use naive Bayes, but it is not true, as the discretization may throw away discriminative information.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Sometimes the distribution of class-conditional marginal densities is far from normal.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] In these cases, kernel density estimation can be used for a more realistic estimate of the marginal densities of each class.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] This method, which was introduced by John and Langley, can boost the accuracy of the classifier considerably.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] With a multinomial event model, samples (feature vectors) represent the frequencies with which certain events have been generated by a multinomial $(p_{1},\dots ,p_{n})$ where $p_{i}$ is the probability that event i occurs (or K such multinomials in the multiclass case).
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] A feature vector $\mathbf {x} =(x_{1},\dots ,x_{n})$ is then a histogram, with $x_{i}$ counting the number of times event i was observed in a particular instance.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] This is the event model typically used for document classification, with events representing the occurrence of a word in a single document (see bag of words assumption).
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Estimating the parameters in log space is advantageous since multiplying a large number of small values can lead to significant rounding error.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Applying a log transform reduces the effect of this rounding error.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] If a given class and feature value never occur together in the training data, then the frequency-based probability estimate will be zero, because the probability estimate is directly proportional to the number of occurrences of a feature's value.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] This is problematic because it will wipe out all information in the other probabilities when they are multiplied.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Therefore, it is often desirable to incorporate a small-sample correction, called pseudocount, in all probability estimates such that no probability is ever set to be exactly zero.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] This way of regularizing naive Bayes is called Laplace smoothing when the pseudocount is one, and Lidstone smoothing in the general case.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] In the multivariate Bernoulli event model, features are independent Boolean variables (binary variables) describing inputs.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Like the multinomial model, this model is popular for document classification tasks, where binary term occurrence features are used rather than term frequencies.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] This event model is especially popular for classifying short texts.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] It has the benefit of explicitly modelling the absence of terms.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Note that a naive Bayes classifier with a Bernoulli event model is not the same as a multinomial NB classifier with frequency counts truncated to one.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Re-train the model based on the *probabilities* (not the labels) predicted in the previous step.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Convergence is determined based on improvement to the model likelihood $P(D\mid \theta )$ , where $\theta$ denotes the parameters of the naive Bayes model.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] This training algorithm is an instance of the more general expectation–maximization algorithm (EM): the prediction step inside the loop is the *E*-step of EM, while the re-training of naive Bayes is the *M*-step.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] The algorithm is formally justified by the assumption that the data are generated by a mixture model, and the components of this mixture model are exactly the classes of the classification problem.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Despite the fact that the far-reaching independence assumptions are often inaccurate, the naive Bayes classifier has several properties that make it surprisingly useful in practice.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] In particular, the decoupling of the class conditional feature distributions means that each distribution can be independently estimated as a one-dimensional distribution.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] This helps alleviate problems stemming from the curse of dimensionality, such as the need for data sets that scale exponentially with the number of features.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] While naive Bayes often fails to produce a good estimate for the correct class probabilities, this may not be a requirement for many applications.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] For example, the naive Bayes classifier will make the correct MAP decision rule classification so long as the correct class is predicted as more probable than any other class.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] This is true regardless of whether the probability estimate is slightly, or even grossly inaccurate.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] In this manner, the overall classifier can be robust enough to ignore serious deficiencies in its underlying naive probability model.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Other reasons for the observed success of the naive Bayes classifier are discussed in the literature cited below.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] This is exactly a logistic regression classifier.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] The link between the two can be seen by observing that the decision function for naive Bayes (in the binary case) can be rewritten as "predict class $C_{1}$ if the odds of $p(C_{1}\mid \mathbf {x} )$ exceed those of $p(C_{2}\mid \mathbf {x} )$ ".
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] The left-hand side of this equation is the log-odds, or *logit*, the quantity predicted by the linear model that underlies logistic regression.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Since naive Bayes is also a linear model for the two "discrete" event models, it can be reparametrised as a linear function $b+\mathbf {w} ^{\top }x>0$ .
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Obtaining the probabilities is then a matter of applying the logistic function to $b+\mathbf {w} ^{\top }x$ , or in the multiclass case, the softmax function.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Discriminative classifiers have lower asymptotic error than generative ones; however, research by Ng and Jordan has shown that in some practical cases naive Bayes can outperform logistic regression because it reaches its asymptotic error faster.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Problem: classify whether a given person is a male or a female based on the measured features.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] The features include height, weight, and foot size.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Although with NB classifier we treat them as independent, they are not in reality.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] The following example assumes equiprobable classes so that P(male)= P(female) = 0.5.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] This prior probability distribution might be based on prior knowledge of frequencies in the larger population or in the training set.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Below is a sample to be classified as male or female.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] In order to classify the sample, one has to determine which posterior is greater, male or female.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] However, given the sample, the evidence is a constant and thus scales both posteriors equally.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] It therefore does not affect classification and can be ignored.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Note that a value greater than 1 is OK here – it is a probability density rather than a probability, because *height* is a continuous variable.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Since posterior numerator is greater in the female case, the prediction is that the sample is female.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Here is a worked example of naive Bayesian classification to the document classification problem.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Consider the problem of classifying documents by their content, for example into spam and non-spam e-mails.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] The question that has to be answered is: "what is the probability that a given document *D* belongs to a given class *C*?" In other words, what is $p(C\mid D)\,$ ?
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Thus, the probability ratio p(*S* | *D*) / p(¬*S* | *D*) can be expressed in terms of a series of likelihood ratios.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] The actual probability p(*S* | *D*) can be easily computed from log (p(*S* | *D*) / p(¬*S* | *D*)) based on the observation that p(*S* | *D*) + p(¬*S* | *D*) = 1.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] (This technique of "log-likelihood ratios" is a common technique in statistics.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Finally, the document can be classified as follows.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] It is spam if $p(S\mid D)>p(\neg S\mid D)$ (i. e., $\ln {p(S\mid D) \over p(\neg S\mid D)}>0$ ), otherwise it is not spam.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Naive Bayes classifiers are a popular statistical technique of e-mail filtering.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] They typically use bag-of-words features to identify email spam, an approach commonly used in text classification.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Naive Bayes classifiers work by correlating the use of tokens (typically words, or sometimes other things), with spam and non-spam e-mails and then using Bayes' theorem to calculate a probability that an email is or is not spam.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Variants of the basic technique have been implemented in a number of research works and commercial software products.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Many modern mail clients implement Bayesian spam filtering.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Users can also install separate email filtering programs.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Server-side email filters, such as DSPAM, Rspamd, SpamAssassin, SpamBayes, Bogofilter, and ASSP, make use of Bayesian spam filtering techniques, and the functionality is sometimes embedded within mail server software itself.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] CRM114, often cited as a Bayesian filter, is not intended to use a Bayes filter in production, but includes the ″unigram″ feature for reference.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] In the case a word has never been met during the learning phase, both the numerator and the denominator are equal to zero, both in the general formula and in the spamicity formula.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] The software can decide to discard such words for which there is no information available.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] More generally, the words that were encountered only a few times during the learning phase cause a problem, because it would be an error to trust blindly the information they provide.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] A simple solution is to simply avoid taking such unreliable words into account as well.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] This corrected probability is used instead of the spamicity in the combining formula.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] This formula can be extended to the case where *n* is equal to zero (and where the spamicity is not defined), and evaluates in this case to $Pr(S)$ .
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] "Neutral" words like "the", "a", "some", or "is" (in English), or their equivalents in other languages, can be ignored.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] More generally, some bayesian filtering filters simply ignore all the words which have a spamicity next to 0.5, as they contribute little to a good decision.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] The words taken into consideration are those whose spamicity is next to 0.0 (distinctive signs of legitimate messages), or next to 1.0 (distinctive signs of spam).
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] A method can be for example to keep only those ten words, in the examined message, which have the greatest absolute value |0.5 − *pI*|.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Some software products take into account the fact that a given word appears several times in the examined message, others don't.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Some software products use *patterns* (sequences of words) instead of isolated natural languages words.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] For example, with a "context window" of four words, they compute the spamicity of "Viagra is good for", instead of computing the spamicities of "Viagra", "is", "good", and "for".
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] This method gives more sensitivity to context and eliminates the Bayesian noise better, at the expense of a bigger database.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Depending on the implementation, Bayesian spam filtering may be susceptible to Bayesian poisoning, a technique used by spammers in an attempt to degrade the effectiveness of spam filters that rely on Bayesian filtering.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] A spammer practicing Bayesian poisoning will send out emails with large amounts of legitimate text (gathered from legitimate news or literary sources).
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Spammer tactics include insertion of random innocuous words that are not normally associated with spam, thereby decreasing the email's spam score, making it more likely to slip past a Bayesian spam filter.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] However, with (for example) Paul Graham's scheme only the most significant probabilities are used, so that padding the text out with non-spam-related words does not affect the detection probability significantly.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Words that normally appear in large quantities in spam may also be transformed by spammers.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] For example, «Viagra» would be replaced with «Viaagra» or «V!agra» in the spam message.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] The recipient of the message can still read the changed words, but each of these words is met more rarely by the Bayesian filter, which hinders its learning process.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] As a general rule, this spamming technique does not work very well, because the derived words end up recognized by the filter just like the normal ones.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Another technique used to try to defeat Bayesian spam filters is to replace text with pictures, either directly included or linked.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] The whole text of the message, or some part of it, is replaced with a picture where the same text is "drawn".
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] The spam filter is usually unable to analyze this picture, which would contain the sensitive words like «Viagra».
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] However, since many mail clients disable the display of linked pictures for security reasons, the spammer sending links to distant pictures might reach fewer targets.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Also, a picture's size in bytes is bigger than the equivalent text's size, so the spammer needs more bandwidth to send messages directly including pictures.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] Some filters are more inclined to decide that a message is spam if it has mostly graphical contents.
[src:text-classification/naive-bayes-classifier] A solution used by Google in its Gmail email system is to perform an OCR (Optical Character Recognition) on every mid to large size image, analyzing the text inside.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] When classification is performed by a computer, statistical methods are normally used to develop the algorithm.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] Often, the individual observations are analyzed into a set of quantifiable properties, known variously as explanatory variables or *features*.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] These properties may variously be categorical (e.g.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] "large", "medium" or "small"), integer-valued (e.g. the number of occurrences of a particular word in an email) or real-valued (e.g. a measurement of blood pressure).
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] Other classifiers work by comparing observations to previous observations by means of a similarity or distance function.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] An algorithm that implements classification, especially in a concrete implementation, is known as a **classifier**.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] The term "classifier" sometimes also refers to the mathematical function, implemented by a classification algorithm, that maps input data to a category.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] Terminology across fields is quite varied.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] In machine learning, the observations are often known as *instances*, the explanatory variables are termed *features* (grouped into a feature vector), and the possible categories to be predicted are *classes*.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] Other fields may use different terminology: e.g. in community ecology, the term "classification" normally refers to cluster analysis.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] Classification and clustering are examples of the more general problem of pattern recognition, which is the assignment of some sort of output value to a given input value.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] A common subclass of classification is probabilistic classification.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] Algorithms of this nature use statistical inference to find the best class for a given instance.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] Unlike other algorithms, which simply output a "best" class, probabilistic algorithms output a probability of the instance being a member of each of the possible classes.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] The best class is normally then selected as the one with the highest probability.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] Early work on statistical classification was undertaken by Fisher, in the context of two-group problems, leading to Fisher's linear discriminant function as the rule for assigning a group to a new observation.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] This early work assumed that data-values within each of the two groups had a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] The extension of this same context to more than two groups has also been considered with a restriction imposed that the classification rule should be linear.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] Unlike frequentist procedures, Bayesian classification procedures provide a natural way of taking into account any available information about the relative sizes of the different groups within the overall population.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] Bayesian procedures tend to be computationally expensive and, in the days before Markov chain Monte Carlo computations were developed, approximations for Bayesian clustering rules were devised.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] Some Bayesian procedures involve the calculation of group-membership probabilities: these provide a more informative outcome than a simple attribution of a single group-label to each new observation.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] Classification can be thought of as two separate problems – binary classification and multiclass classification.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] In binary classification, a better understood task, only two classes are involved, whereas multiclass classification involves assigning an object to one of several classes.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] Since many classification methods have been developed specifically for binary classification, multiclass classification often requires the combined use of multiple binary classifiers.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] Most algorithms describe an individual instance whose category is to be predicted using a feature vector of individual, measurable properties of the instance.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] Each property is termed a feature, also known in statistics as an explanatory variable (or independent variable, although features may or may not be statistically independent).
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] "large", "medium" or "small"); integer-valued (e.g. the number of occurrences of a particular word in an email); or real-valued (e.g. a measurement of blood pressure).
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] If the instance is an image, the feature values might correspond to the pixels of an image; if the instance is a piece of text, the feature values might be occurrence frequencies of different words.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] Some algorithms work only in terms of discrete data and require that real-valued or integer-valued data be *discretized* into groups (e.g. less than 5, between 5 and 10, or greater than 10).
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] A large number of algorithms for classification can be phrased in terms of a linear function that assigns a score to each possible category *k* by combining the feature vector of an instance with a vector of weights, using a dot product.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] The predicted category is the one with the highest score.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] In discrete choice theory, where instances represent people and categories represent choices, the score is considered the utility associated with person *i* choosing category *k*.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] Algorithms with this basic setup are known as linear classifiers.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] What distinguishes them is the procedure for determining (training) the optimal weights/coefficients and the way that the score is interpreted.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] Since no single form of classification is appropriate for all data sets, a large toolkit of classification algorithms has been developed.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] Choices between different possible algorithms are frequently made on the basis of quantitative evaluation of accuracy.
[src:text-classification/statistical-classification] In some of these, it is employed as a data mining procedure, while in others more detailed statistical modeling is undertaken.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] In machine learning, **support vector machines** (**SVMs**, also **support vector networks**) are supervised max-margin models with associated learning algorithms that analyze data for classification and regression analysis.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Developed at AT&T Bell Laboratories, SVMs are one of the most studied models, being based on statistical learning frameworks of VC theory proposed by Vapnik (1982, 1995) and Chervonenkis (1974).
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Thus, SVMs use the kernel trick to implicitly map their inputs into high-dimensional feature spaces, where linear classification can be performed.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Being max-margin models, SVMs are resilient to noisy data (e.g., misclassified examples).
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] SVMs can also be used for regression tasks, where the objective becomes $\epsilon$ -sensitive.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The support vector clustering algorithm, created by Hava Siegelmann and Vladimir Vapnik, applies the statistics of support vectors, developed in the support vector machines algorithm, to categorize unlabeled data.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] These data sets require unsupervised learning approaches, which attempt to find natural clustering of the data into groups, and then to map new data according to these clusters.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The popularity of SVMs is likely due to their amenability to theoretical analysis, and their flexibility in being applied to a wide variety of tasks, including structured prediction problems.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] It is not clear that SVMs have better predictive performance than other linear models, such as logistic regression and linear regression.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Classifying data is a common task in machine learning.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Suppose some given data points each belong to one of two classes, and the goal is to decide which class a *new* data point will be in.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] In the case of support vector machines, a data point is viewed as a p -dimensional vector (a list of p numbers), and we want to know whether we can separate such points with a $(p-1)$ -dimensional hyperplane.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] There are many hyperplanes that might classify the data.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] One reasonable choice as the best hyperplane is the one that represents the largest separation, or margin, between the two classes.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] So we choose the hyperplane so that the distance from it to the nearest data point on each side is maximized.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] If such a hyperplane exists, it is known as the *maximum-margin hyperplane* and the linear classifier it defines is known as a *maximum-margin classifier*; or equivalently, the *perceptron of optimal stability*.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] More formally, a support vector machine constructs a hyperplane or set of hyperplanes in a high or infinite-dimensional space, which can be used for classification, regression, or other tasks like outlier detection.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Intuitively, a good separation is achieved by the hyperplane that has the largest distance to the nearest training-data point of any class (so-called functional margin), since in general the larger the margin, the lower the generalization error of the classifier.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] A lower generalization error means that the implementer is less likely to experience overfitting.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Whereas the original problem may be stated in a finite-dimensional space, it often happens that the sets to discriminate are not linearly separable in that space.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] For this reason, it was proposed that the original finite-dimensional space be mapped into a much higher-dimensional space, presumably making the separation easier in that space.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The hyperplanes in the higher-dimensional space are defined as the set of points whose dot product with a vector in that space is constant, where such a set of vectors is an orthogonal (and thus minimal) set of vectors that defines a hyperplane.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The vectors defining the hyperplanes can be chosen to be linear combinations with parameters $\alpha _{i}$ of images of feature vectors $x_{i}$ that occur in the data base.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] In this way, the sum of kernels above can be used to measure the relative nearness of each test point to the data points originating in one or the other of the sets to be discriminated.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Note the fact that the set of points x mapped into any hyperplane can be quite convoluted as a result, allowing much more complex discrimination between sets that are not convex at all in the original space.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The original SVM algorithm was invented by Vladimir N.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] In 1992, Bernhard Boser, Isabelle Guyon and Vladimir Vapnik suggested a way to create nonlinear classifiers by applying the kernel trick to maximum-margin hyperplanes.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The "soft margin" incarnation, as is commonly used in software packages, was proposed by Corinna Cortes and Vapnik in 1993 and published in 1995.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] We are given a training dataset of n points of the form $(\mathbf {x} _{1},y_{1}),\ldots ,(\mathbf {x} _{n},y_{n}),$ where the $y_{i}$ are either 1 or −1, each indicating the class to which the point $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ belongs.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Each $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ is a p -dimensional real vector.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Any hyperplane can be written as the set of points $\mathbf {x}$ satisfying $\mathbf {w} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {x} -b=0,$ where $\mathbf {w}$ is the (not necessarily normalized) normal vector to the hyperplane.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] This is much like Hesse normal form, except that $\mathbf {w}$ is not necessarily a unit vector.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The parameter ${\tfrac {b}{\|\mathbf {w} \|}}$ determines the offset of the hyperplane from the origin along the normal vector $\mathbf {w}$ .
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] If the training data is linearly separable, we can select two parallel hyperplanes that separate the two classes of data, so that the distance between them is as large as possible.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The region bounded by these two hyperplanes is called the "margin", and the maximum-margin hyperplane is the hyperplane that lies halfway between them.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] (anything on or below this boundary is of the other class, with label −1).
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Geometrically, the distance between these two hyperplanes is ${\tfrac {2}{\|\mathbf {w} \|}}$ , so to maximize the distance between the planes we want to minimize $\|\mathbf {w} \|$ .
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The distance is computed using the distance from a point to a plane equation.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The $\mathbf {w}$ and b that solve this problem determine the final classifier, $\mathbf {x} \mapsto \operatorname {sgn}(\mathbf {w} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {x} -b)$ , where $\operatorname {sgn}(\cdot )$ is the sign function.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] An important consequence of this geometric description is that the max-margin hyperplane is completely determined by those $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ that lie nearest to it (explained below).
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] These $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ are called *support vectors*.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] This function is zero if the constraint in **(1)** is satisfied, in other words, if $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ lies on the correct side of the margin.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] For data on the wrong side of the margin, the function's value is proportional to the distance from the margin.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] where the parameter $C>0$ determines the trade-off between increasing the margin size and ensuring that the $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ lie on the correct side of the margin (Note we can add a weight to either term in the equation above).
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Thus, for large values of C , it will behave similar to the hard-margin SVM, if the input data are linearly classifiable, but will still learn if a classification rule is viable or not.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The original maximum-margin hyperplane algorithm proposed by Vapnik in 1963 constructed a linear classifier.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] However, in 1992, Bernhard Boser, Isabelle Guyon and Vladimir Vapnik suggested a way to create nonlinear classifiers by applying the kernel trick (originally proposed by Aizerman et al.) to maximum-margin hyperplanes.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The kernel trick, where dot products are replaced by kernels, is easily derived in the dual representation of the SVM problem.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] This allows the algorithm to fit the maximum-margin hyperplane in a transformed feature space.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The transformation may be nonlinear and the transformed space high-dimensional; although the classifier is a hyperplane in the transformed feature space, it may be nonlinear in the original input space.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] It is noteworthy that working in a higher-dimensional feature space increases the generalization error of support vector machines, although given enough samples the algorithm still performs well.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The kernel is related to the transform $\varphi (\mathbf {x} _{i})$ by the equation $k(\mathbf {x} _{i},\mathbf {x} _{j})=\varphi (\mathbf {x} _{i})\cdot \varphi (\mathbf {x} _{j})$ .
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The value **w** is also in the transformed space, with ${\textstyle \mathbf {w} =\sum _{i}\alpha _{i}y_{i}\varphi (\mathbf {x} _{i})}$ .
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Dot products with **w** for classification can again be computed by the kernel trick, i.e. ${\textstyle \mathbf {w} \cdot \varphi (\mathbf {x} )=\sum _{i}\alpha _{i}y_{i}k(\mathbf {x} _{i},\mathbf {x} )}$ .
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] We focus on the soft-margin classifier since, as noted above, choosing a sufficiently small value for $\lambda$ yields the hard-margin classifier for linearly classifiable input data.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The classical approach, which involves reducing **(2)** to a quadratic programming problem, is detailed below.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Then, more recent approaches such as sub-gradient descent and coordinate descent will be discussed.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Minimizing **(2)** can be rewritten as a constrained optimization problem with a differentiable objective function in the following way.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Since the dual maximization problem is a quadratic function of the $c_{i}$ subject to linear constraints, it is efficiently solvable by quadratic programming algorithms.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Moreover, $c_{i}=0$ exactly when $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ lies on the correct side of the margin, and $0<c_{i}<(2n\lambda )^{-1}$ when $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ lies on the margin's boundary.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] It follows that $\mathbf {w}$ can be written as a linear combination of the support vectors.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The coefficients $c_{i}$ can be solved for using quadratic programming, as before.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Recent algorithms for finding the SVM classifier include sub-gradient descent and coordinate descent.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Both techniques have proven to offer significant advantages over the traditional approach when dealing with large, sparse datasets—sub-gradient methods are especially efficient when there are many training examples, and coordinate descent when the dimension of the feature space is high.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Note that f is a convex function of $\mathbf {w}$ and b .
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] As such, traditional gradient descent (or SGD) methods can be adapted, where instead of taking a step in the direction of the function's gradient, a step is taken in the direction of a vector selected from the function's sub-gradient.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] This approach has the advantage that, for certain implementations, the number of iterations does not scale with n , the number of data points.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] For each $i\in \{1,\,\ldots ,\,n\}$ , iteratively, the coefficient $c_{i}$ is adjusted in the direction of $\partial f/\partial c_{i}$ .
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Then, the resulting vector of coefficients $(c_{1}',\,\ldots ,\,c_{n}')$ is projected onto the nearest vector of coefficients that satisfies the given constraints.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] (Typically Euclidean distances are used.) The process is then repeated until a near-optimal vector of coefficients is obtained.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The resulting algorithm is extremely fast in practice, although few performance guarantees have been proven.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The soft-margin support vector machine described above is an example of an empirical risk minimization (ERM) algorithm for the *hinge loss*.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Seen this way, support vector machines belong to a natural class of algorithms for statistical inference, and many of its unique features are due to the behavior of the hinge loss.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] This perspective can provide further insight into how and why SVMs work, and allow us to better analyze their statistical properties.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] In supervised learning, one is given a set of training examples $X_{1}\ldots X_{n}$ with labels $y_{1}\ldots y_{n}$ , and wishes to predict $y_{n+1}$ given $X_{n+1}$ .
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] To do so one forms a hypothesis, f , such that $f(X_{n+1})$ is a "good" approximation of $y_{n+1}$ .
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] A "good" approximation is usually defined with the help of a *loss function,* $\ell (y,z)$ , which characterizes how bad z is as a prediction of y .
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] In most cases, we don't know the joint distribution of $X_{n+1},\,y_{n+1}$ outright.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] This approach is called *empirical risk minimization,* or ERM.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] In order for the minimization problem to have a well-defined solution, we have to place constraints on the set ${\mathcal {H}}$ of hypotheses being considered.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] If ${\mathcal {H}}$ is a normed space (as is the case for SVM), a particularly effective technique is to consider only those hypotheses f for which $\lVert f\rVert _{\mathcal {H}}<k$ .
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] More generally, ${\mathcal {R}}(f)$ can be some measure of the complexity of the hypothesis f , so that simpler hypotheses are preferred.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] From this perspective, SVM is closely related to other fundamental classification algorithms such as regularized least-squares and logistic regression.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The difference between the hinge loss and these other loss functions is best stated in terms of *target functions -* the function that minimizes expected risk for a given pair of random variables $X,\,y$ .
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] In particular, let $y_{x}$ denote y conditional on the event that $X=x$ .
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] For the square-loss, the target function is the conditional expectation function, $f_{sq}(x)=\mathbb {E} \left[y_{x}\right]$ ; For the logistic loss, it's the logit function, $f_{\log }(x)=\ln \left(p_{x}/({1-p_{x}})\right)$ .
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] While both of these target functions yield the correct classifier, as $\operatorname {sgn}(f_{sq})=\operatorname {sgn}(f_{\log })=f^{*}$ , they give us more information than we need.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] In fact, they give us enough information to completely describe the distribution of $y_{x}$ .
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] On the other hand, one can check that the target function for the hinge loss is *exactly* $f^{*}$ .
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Thus, in a sufficiently rich hypothesis space—or equivalently, for an appropriately chosen kernel—the SVM classifier will converge to the simplest function (in terms of ${\mathcal {R}}$ ) that correctly classifies the data.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] This extends the geometric interpretation of SVM—for linear classification, the empirical risk is minimized by any function whose margins lie between the support vectors, and the simplest of these is the max-margin classifier.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] SVMs belong to a family of generalized linear classifiers and can be interpreted as an extension of the perceptron.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] They can also be considered a special case of Tikhonov regularization.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] A special property is that they simultaneously minimize the empirical *classification error* and maximize the *geometric margin*; hence they are also known as **maximum margin classifiers**.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] A comparison of the SVM to other classifiers has been made by Meyer, Leisch and Hornik.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The effectiveness of SVM depends on the selection of kernel, the kernel's parameters, and soft margin parameter $\lambda$ .
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] A common choice is a Gaussian kernel, which has a single parameter *$\gamma$*.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Typically, each combination of parameter choices is checked using cross validation, and the parameters with best cross-validation accuracy are picked.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Alternatively, recent work in Bayesian optimization can be used to select $\lambda$ and *$\gamma$* , often requiring the evaluation of far fewer parameter combinations than grid search.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The final model, which is used for testing and for classifying new data, is then trained on the whole training set using the selected parameters.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Multiclass SVM aims to assign labels to instances by using support vector machines, where the labels are drawn from a finite set of several elements.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The dominant approach for doing so is to reduce the single multiclass problem into multiple binary classification problems.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Crammer and Singer proposed a multiclass SVM method which casts the multiclass classification problem into a single optimization problem, rather than decomposing it into multiple binary classification problems.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] See also Lee, Lin and Wahba and Van den Burg and Groenen.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Transductive support vector machines extend SVMs in that they could also treat partially labeled data in semi-supervised learning by following the principles of transduction.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Transductive support vector machines were introduced by Vladimir N.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Structured support-vector machine is an extension of the traditional SVM model.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] While the SVM model is primarily designed for binary classification, multiclass classification, and regression tasks, structured SVM broadens its application to handle general structured output labels, for example parse trees, classification with taxonomies, sequence alignment and many more.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] A version of SVM for regression was proposed in 1996 by Vladimir N.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] This method is called support vector regression (SVR).
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The model produced by support vector classification (as described above) depends only on a subset of the training data, because the cost function for building the model does not care about training points that lie beyond the margin.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Analogously, the model produced by SVR depends only on a subset of the training data, because the cost function for building the model ignores any training data close to the model prediction.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Another SVM version known as least-squares support vector machine (LS-SVM) has been proposed by Suykens and Vandewalle.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] where $x_{i}$ is a training sample with target value $y_{i}$ .
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The inner product plus intercept $\langle w,x_{i}\rangle +b$ is the prediction for that sample, and $\varepsilon$ is a free parameter that serves as a threshold: all predictions have to be within an $\varepsilon$ range of the true predictions.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Slack variables are usually added into the above to allow for errors and to allow approximation in the case the above problem is infeasible.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] In 2011 it was shown by Polson and Scott that the SVM admits a Bayesian interpretation through the technique of data augmentation.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] In this approach the SVM is viewed as a graphical model (where the parameters are connected via probability distributions).
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] This extended view allows the application of Bayesian techniques to SVMs, such as flexible feature modeling, automatic hyperparameter tuning, and predictive uncertainty quantification.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] In 2017, a scalable version of the Bayesian SVM was developed by Florian Wenzel, enabling the application of Bayesian SVMs to big data.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Florian Wenzel developed two different versions, a variational inference (VI) scheme for the Bayesian kernel support vector machine (SVM) and a stochastic version (SVI) for the linear Bayesian SVM.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The parameters of the maximum-margin hyperplane are derived by solving the optimization.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] There exist several specialized algorithms for quickly solving the quadratic programming (QP) problem that arises from SVMs, mostly relying on heuristics for breaking the problem down into smaller, more manageable chunks.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Another approach is to use an interior-point method that uses Newton-like iterations to find a solution of the Karush–Kuhn–Tucker conditions of the primal and dual problems.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Instead of solving a sequence of broken-down problems, this approach directly solves the problem altogether.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] To avoid solving a linear system involving the large kernel matrix, a low-rank approximation to the matrix is often used in the kernel trick.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Another common method is Platt's sequential minimal optimization (SMO) algorithm, which breaks the problem down into 2-dimensional sub-problems that are solved analytically, eliminating the need for a numerical optimization algorithm and matrix storage.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] This algorithm is conceptually simple, easy to implement, generally faster, and has better scaling properties for difficult SVM problems.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The special case of linear support vector machines can be solved more efficiently by the same kind of algorithms used to optimize its close cousin, logistic regression; this class of algorithms includes sub-gradient descent (e.g., PEGASOS) and coordinate descent (e.g., LIBLINEAR).
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] LIBLINEAR has some attractive training-time properties.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Each convergence iteration takes time linear in the time taken to read the train data, and the iterations also have a Q-linear convergence property, making the algorithm extremely fast.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] The general kernel SVMs can also be solved more efficiently using sub-gradient descent (e.g.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] P-packSVM), especially when parallelization is allowed.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Kernel SVMs are available in many machine-learning toolkits, including LIBSVM, MATLAB, SAS, SVMlight, kernlab, scikit-learn, Shogun, Weka, Shark, JKernelMachines, OpenCV and others.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Preprocessing of data (standardization) is highly recommended to enhance accuracy of classification.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] There are a few methods of standardization, such as min-max, normalization by decimal scaling, Z-score.
[src:text-classification/support-vector-machine] Subtraction of mean and division by variance of each feature is usually used for SVM.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] In information retrieval, **tf–idf** (**term frequency–inverse document frequency**, **TF*IDF**, **TFIDF**, **TF–IDF**, or **Tf–idf**) is a measure of importance of a word to a document in a collection or corpus, adjusted for the fact that some words appear more frequently in general.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] Like the bag-of-words model, it models a document as a multiset of words, without word order.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] It is a refinement over the simple bag-of-words model, by allowing the weight of words to depend on the rest of the corpus.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] It was often used as a weighting factor in searches of information retrieval, text mining, and user modeling.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] A survey conducted in 2015 showed that 83% of text-based recommender systems in digital libraries used tf–idf.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] Variations of the tf–idf weighting scheme were often used by search engines as a central tool in scoring and ranking a document's relevance given a user query.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] One of the simplest ranking functions is computed by summing the tf–idf for each query term; many more sophisticated ranking functions are variants of this simple model.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] We see that "Romeo", "Falstaff", and "salad" appears in very few plays, so seeing these words, one could get a good idea as to which play it might be.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] In contrast, "good" and "sweet" appears in every play and are completely uninformative as to which play it is.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] A formula that aims to define the importance of a keyword or phrase within a document or a web page.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] where *f**t*,*d* is the *raw count* of a term in a document, i.e., the number of times that term t occurs in document d.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] Note the denominator is simply the total number of terms in document *d* (counting each occurrence of the same term separately).
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] The **inverse document frequency** is a measure of how much information the word provides, i.e., how common or rare it is across all documents.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] A high weight in tf–idf is reached by a high term frequency (in the given document) and a low document frequency of the term in the whole collection of documents; the weights hence tend to filter out common terms.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] Since the ratio inside the idf's log function is always greater than or equal to 1, the value of idf (and tf–idf) is greater than or equal to 0.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] As a term appears in more documents, the ratio inside the logarithm approaches 1, bringing the idf and tf–idf closer to 0.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] Idf was introduced as "term specificity" by Karen Spärck Jones in a 1972 paper.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] Although it has worked well as a heuristic, its theoretical foundations have been troublesome for at least three decades afterward, with many researchers trying to find information theoretic justifications for it.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] Spärck Jones's own explanation did not propose much theory, aside from a connection to Zipf's law.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] Namely, the inverse document frequency is the logarithm of "inverse" relative document frequency.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] This probabilistic interpretation in turn takes the same form as that of self-information.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] However, applying such information-theoretic notions to problems in information retrieval leads to problems when trying to define the appropriate event spaces for the required probability distributions: not only documents need to be taken into account, but also queries and terms.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] Both term frequency and inverse document frequency can be formulated in terms of information theory; it helps to understand why their product has a meaning in terms of joint informational content of a document.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] In terms of notation, ${\cal {D}}$ and ${\cal {T}}$ are "random variables" corresponding to respectively draw a document or a term.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] This expression shows that summing the Tf–idf of all possible terms and documents recovers the mutual information between documents and term taking into account all the specificities of their joint distribution.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] Each Tf–idf hence carries the "bit of information" attached to a term x document pair.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] Tf–idf is closely related to the negative logarithmically transformed *p*-value from a one-tailed formulation of Fisher's exact test when the underlying corpus documents satisfy certain idealized assumptions.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] More recently, tf–idf variants were shown to arise as components in the test statistic of a penalized likelihood-ratio test for word burstiness based on a beta-binomial statistical language model.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] In this framework, the null hypothesis models term occurrences using a binomial distribution, while the alternative hypothesis models word burstiness using a beta-binomial distribution with a gamma-distributed penalty term placed on the beta-binomial precision parameter.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] The resulting test statistic contains the tf–idf variants binary term frequency–inverse document frequency (btf–idf) and term frequency–inverse collection frequency (tf–icf), thereby establishing a direct connection between tf–idf family term-weighting schemes and statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] In its raw frequency form, tf is just the frequency of the "this" for each document.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] In each document, the word "this" appears once; but as the document 2 has more words, its relative frequency is smaller.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] An idf is constant per corpus, and **accounts** for the ratio of documents that include the word "this".
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] In this case, we have a corpus of two documents and all of them include the word "this".
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] So tf–idf is zero for the word "this", which implies that the word is not very informative as it appears in all documents.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] The idea behind tf–idf also applies to entities other than terms.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] In 1998, the concept of idf was applied to citations.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] The authors argued that "if a very uncommon citation is shared by two documents, this should be weighted more highly than a citation made by a large number of documents".
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] In addition, tf–idf was applied to "visual words" with the purpose of conducting object matching in videos, and entire sentences.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] However, the concept of tf–idf did not prove to be more effective in all cases than a plain tf scheme (without idf).
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] When tf–idf was applied to citations, researchers could find no improvement over a simple citation-count weight that had no idf component.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] A number of term-weighting schemes have derived from tf–idf.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] One of them is TF–PDF (term frequency * proportional document frequency).
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] TF–PDF was introduced in 2001 in the context of identifying emerging topics in the media.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] The PDF component measures the difference of how often a term occurs in different domains.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] In TF–IDuF, idf is not calculated based on the document corpus that is to be searched or recommended.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] Instead, idf is calculated on users' personal document collections.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] The authors report that TF–IDuF was equally effective as tf–idf but could also be applied in situations when, e.g., a user modeling system has no access to a global document corpus.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] The DELTA TF-IDF derivative uses the difference in importance of a term across two specific classes, like positive and negative sentiment.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] For example, it can assign a high score to a word like "excellent" in positive reviews and a low score to the same word in negative reviews.
[src:text-classification/tf-idf] This helps identify words that strongly indicate the sentiment of a document, potentially leading to improved accuracy in text classification tasks.
